          <h1>Industrial Irradiation</h1>
          <p> <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><br>
            </font></p>
          <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">There are a
              great many industries using radiation in the production, quality
              assurance, and sterilization of products.</font></p>
          <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">Radiation is
              becoming a common tool in the production of synthetic materials
              and natural rubber products (hardening and polymer </font><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">cross-linking).&nbsp;
              The radiation is used for annealing and polymerization without the
              negative effects of heat processing.&nbsp; Most wiring in your
              car's engine compartment have been through some sort of radiation
              processing to make them more heat resistant.&nbsp; </font></p>
          <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"> Radiation is
              used to test spacecraft electronics for space environments.&nbsp;
              In addition, radiation is used to "harden" spacecraft
              semiconductors to be more radiation tolerant.&nbsp; In fact,
              without radiation testing and hardening, most satellites would not
              currently be operating now.</font></p>
          <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">Various gauges
              using radioactive materials are used to measure quantities such as
              the thickness of materials, the flow rate of liquids, and the
              level of material in tanks.&nbsp; Radiation is also used to </font><font
              face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">check the quality of
              metals and welds (see Non-De</font><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">structive
              Testing) </font></p>
          <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">Radiation is
              used to cold pasteurize food (see Food Irradiation) and sterilize
              medical products. It is a very cost-effective way to destroy
              bacteria and viruses in products intended for people with
              suppressed immune systems.</font> </p>
          <p align="justify"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">The
              other common use of industrial irradiation is for inspection of
              packages. For example, every time you go to the airport, your
              luggage is interrogated with radiation. The industrial
              applications are everywhere!</font></p>
          <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><em> </em></font>
